voice_to_text: Hey APUSH students! Here are five must know elections for your midterm! First is the Election of 1800, and you definitely want to know context. And the Quasi War with France and the Alien and Sedition Acts made John Adams a pretty unpopular president. So for your test, you definitely want to remember that Jefferson's election is known as the Revolution of 1800, because it's the first time America peacefully transferred power from one party to the next. You could definitely see an excerpt from Jefferson's inaugural address, where he stated â€œWe are all Republicans, we are all Federalistsâ€ which promoted unity after this revolutionary election. Second, we have the Election of 1824. This election has four candidates, John Quincy Adams, Andrew Jackson, Henry Clay, and William Crawford. But nobody won the majority in the Electoral College, so it went to the House of Representatives. Ok here's where it gets juicy! The House of Representatives, which was led by Henry Clay, chose John Quincy Adams to be the president, and Adams quickly chose Henry Clay to be Secretary of State. This led to accusations of a â€œCorrupt Bargainâ€. Remember that all this bad blood surrounding this election led to the end of the Era of Good Feelings. And be ready for questions about how this election led to the rise of Andrew Jackson and the birth of Jacksonian Democracy. The common man supporters of Andrew Jackson felt like they had been robbed and they made sure he won the election in 1828. Third is the election of 1844, which has two main characters, Henry Clay and James K. Polk. And the main issue was Manifest Destiny. Polk campaigned for the annexation of Texas and the occupation of the Oregon Territory with his slogan  â€œFifty-Four Forty or Fightâ€. Polk won and his administration witnessed unprecedented territorial expansion. Think Texas, Oregon, California, America was expanding all over the map. And his presidency oversaw the Mexican-American War and the Mexican Cession. Fourth is the Election of 1860, and this is a big one! The central issue was slavery and its expansion into the territories. The Democrat Party was split between a northern and southern candidate, so Abraham Lincoln won without a single southern state voting for him. So for your test you definitely want to focus on the effects. Lincoln's victory convinced southern states that they had lost their voice in national politics and they began seceding from the union, setting the stage for the Civil War. And pretty much all of Lincoln's presidency will be consumed by this war to preserve the Union, and it will forever change the course of the nation. And last but not least is the Election of 1876. To fully understand the significance of this election, we need to rewind to the aftermath of the Civil War and the period known as Reconstruction. The nation was struggling to rebuild and redefine itself and tensions were high, especially in southern states. And the Election of 1876 between Republican Rutherford B. Hayes and Democrat Samuel J Tilden became a turning point for these tensions. The election results were disputed leading to what's known as the Compromise of 1877. In exchange for Rutherford B. Hayes being declared the winner, the Republicans agreed to withdraw federal troops from the southern states, effectively ending Reconstruction. And for your test, focus on the big picture. With federal troops being gone, Southern Democrats regained control of the South through Jim Crow laws and even violence. So there are your must know elections for your midterm, and as always, for more APUSH help, make sure you check out the Ultimate Review Packet!

Barbi Benton (born Barbara Lynn Klein; January 28, 1950) is an American retired model, actress, television personality, and singer. She is known for appearing in #Playboy magazine, as a four-season regular on the comedy series #HeeHaw, and for recording several modestly successful albums in the 1970s. After the birth of her first child in 1986, Benton retired from show business to raise her family.  At the age of 16, she began to model. Following high school, while attending UCLA, Benton took a job with Playboy to appear on their entertainment show Playboy After Dark at age 18. She initially started as an extra on the show, but after host #HughHefner fell in love with Benton, her role was quickly elevated to co-host. After recording two episodes, Hefner asked the young co-ed for a date. Upon being asked, she reportedly demurred to the then-42-year-old Hefner: "I don't know, I've never dated anyone over 24 before." To which Hefner replied, "That's all right, neither have I." The two began a relationship that lasted several years, and placed Benton in the center of the Playboy enterprise. Hefner persuaded her to change her name from Barbara Klein to the more "marketable" Barbi Benton. She is credited with persuading Hefner to buy the #PlayboyMansion in #HolmbyHills in 1974. The morning I found out Grandpa passed away I went to take a shower (great place to cry) and like usual put on my favorite podcast Keep It. They had been ranking their favorite songs from their various artists and when I paused it they were talking about Janet Jackson. When i hit play the words â€œTogether Againâ€ came out of my phone then stopped. Iâ€™m not sure what is on the other side of our physical reality but I know that I immediately put the song on and knew it was exactly what I needed to hear. When my mom found this incredible biodegradable seashell (in their favorite color coral) it felt like kismet. I spent a lot of time thinking about how I could best honor them and it felt right to do it with flowers. I knew it had to have coral and lots of colors and metallics. Vera was a flashy lady who lived in hyper color. Iâ€™ll never forget doodling with her copying dresses the latest celebs were wearing in her stacks of National Enquirer magazines. She taught me to not be afraid of color and how to express myself. I really have her to thank for all of this. My original muse. On the way to the sailboat my arrangement tipped over in the car. If youâ€™re an artist you understand the devastation and how personal making art is let alone in the honor of your loved ones. It was the only thing I felt I could control during all of this and having it tip over felt like losing control of the only grip I had. It turned out for the best because ripping apart the non-painted rose petals and tossing them into the ocean with my family was the perfect way to send those lovebirds off. Grandma and Grandpa Iâ€™ll miss you both forever and Iâ€™ll continue to honor you both by prioritizing being a loving person that has the capacity to pivot when things get messy. Itâ€™s like I always say when Iâ€™m designing â€œif Iâ€™m not making a mess doing it Iâ€™m not going as hard as I need to beâ€ the mess is always half the fun when it comes to expression. A chaotic trade off to what you create for the world. video_description: ğ—¦ğ—œğ—¦ğ—§ğ—˜ğ—¥ ğ—§ğ—›ğ—˜ğ—” ğ—•ğ—¢ğ—ªğ— ğ—”ğ—¡ (1937 â€“ 1990) Sister Thea Bowman was a Catholic Franciscan nun, evangelist, and educator known for introducing culturally inclusive practices into the Catholic liturgy. Her contributions were so significant that she is being considered for sainthood. Thea Bowman was born Bertha Elizabeth Bowman on December 29, 1937, in Yazoo City, Mississippi. Her mother, Mary Esther (Coleman), was a teacher, and her father, Theon Edward, was a physician. Bowman grew up in Canton, Mississippi. Although her parents were Methodists, she attended the Holy Child Jesus School, a Catholic school for African American children. She was greatly influenced by her teachers, who were members of the Franciscan Sisters of Perpetual Adoration (FSPA), a religious order from La Crosse, Wisconsin.  When she was eight or nine years old, she asked her parents for permission to convert to Catholicism. Then, at age fifteen, Bowman moved north to study at the St. Rose Convent in La Crosse. When she joined the order in 1953, she was the FSPAâ€™s first African American nun. She was given the name Sister Mary Thea, in honor of the Blessed Mother and her father, Theon. Sister Bowman trained to become a teacher and taught on every level. She earned her B.A. in English, Speech and Drama in 1965 from nearby Viterbo College (now University). She received her M.A. in English in 1969 and a Ph.D. in English Language, Literature, and Linguistics in 1972, both from The Catholic University of America in Washington, D.C.  She was an elementary teacher at Blessed Sacrament School in La Crosse and a high school teacher at Holy Child High School in Canton, Mississippi. In the 1970s, she taught English for several years at Viterbo. As a graduate student, she created the first Black literature course at Catholic University. Later, Bowman was on the faculty at Xavier University of Louisiana, the only Catholic HBCU. At Xavier, she was one of the founding members of the master of theology program and the Institute of Black Catholic Studies (1980). In addition to teaching, Sister Bowman traveled widely in the United States and abroad, giving public speeches and lectures, short courses and workshops. Through song, dance, stories and poetry, she spread her message of joy, freedom, and pride in her culture. She argued that the Catholic Church should be more inclusive, taking into account the cultural practices of its diverse membership. To that end, she was instrumental in the publication of Lead Me, Guide Me: An African American Catholic Hymnal (1987). In 1978, Bowman returned to Canton to care for her aging parents. She was appointed to direct the Office of Intercultural Affairs for the Diocese of Jackson, where she continued to spread the message of diversity and inclusion. Her parents died in 1984, and that same year, she was diagnosed with breast cancer. Throughout her treatment, Sister Bowman continued to keep a rigorous schedule of engagements, although she was eventually confined to a wheelchair. In 1987, she was profiled on the CBS news magazine 60 Minutes. One of her last public speeches was in June of 1989, addressing the United States Conference of Catholic Bishops at their annual meeting held at Seton Hall University, South Orange, New Jersey. The same year, Bowman was the first African American woman to receive an honorary Doctor of Religion from Boston College. #fyp #foryourpage #dailyhistoryfactoftheday

video_description: John Fitzgerald Kennedy, often referred to as JFK, was the 35th President of the United States, serving from January 1961 until his tragic assassination in November 1963. Born on May 29, 1917, in Brookline, Massachusetts, Kennedy came from a politically prominent family and was the second son of Joseph P. Kennedy, a wealthy businessman and ambassador. Kennedy's political career began when he was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in 1946, and later, he served as a senator from Massachusetts. His charisma and eloquence quickly distinguished him, making him a rising star in American politics. In 1960, Kennedy secured the Democratic nomination for president and went on to narrowly defeat Richard Nixon in one of the closest elections in U.S. history. As president, JFK faced numerous challenges, both domestically and internationally. One of his most notable achievements was the establishment of the Peace Corps in 1961, which aimed to promote peace and friendship by providing volunteer assistance in developing countries. Kennedy's advocacy for civil rights also marked a pivotal moment in American history. He addressed the nation on June 11, 1963, declaring that segregation was morally wrong and announcing his intention to introduce comprehensive civil rights legislation. On the international front, Kennedy navigated the tense relations of the Cold War, particularly during the Cuban Missile Crisis in 1962. His skillful diplomacy and resolve helped avert a nuclear confrontation between the United States and the Soviet Union. Kennedy's commitment to space exploration was evident in his famous 1961 speech, where he set the ambitious goal of landing an American on the moon before the end of the decade. This vision eventually materialized in 1969, with the Apollo 11 mission. Tragically, Kennedy's presidency was cut short on November 22, 1963, when he was assassinated during a motorcade in Dallas, Texas. His death had a profound impact on the nation, leading to widespread mourning and a sense of lost potential. The Warren Commission, which investigated the assassination, concluded that Lee Harvey Oswald acted alone, but conspiracy theories persist to this day. In conclusion, John F. Kennedy's presidency is remembered for its idealism, charm, and commitment to progress. His leadership during challenging times left an indelible mark on the United States, and his legacy continues to be a source of inspiration for generations. #fyp #fy #fypã‚·

video_description: FranÃ§ois "Papa Doc" Duvalier was the president of Haiti from 1957 to 1971. His son Jean-Claude "Baby Doc" Duvalier took office in 1971 and a popular uprising ousted him in 1986. The Duvalierist regime lasted longer than any other Haitian government, which continued after Baby Doc fled the country. This period was Duvalierism without Duvalier. General Henri Namphy of the Haitian military was the first of a string of Duvalierist military leaders who led Haiti until the election of Jean-Betrand Aristide in 1990. FRANÃ‡OIS DUVALIER was born on April 14, 1907. His father, Duval Duvalier, was born in Martinique and worked as a schoolteacher in Haiti. Duval Duvalier's occupation placed his family firmly into the new middle class created, partially, by the U.S. military occupation of Haiti (1915-1934). Duvalier studied under prominent Haitian nationalists such as Jean Price-Mars and Dumarsais Estime, who was president of Haiti from 1946-1950. Duvalier joined the Bureau of Ethnology founded by Jacques Romain, while under the directorship of Jean Price-Mars. Through them, he participated in the budding Negritude movement and its local Haitian variant, the Indigenist movement. He received his medical degree in 1934 and studied public health at the University of Michigan in 1943. In 1944, Duvalier became part of the Inter-American Commission's $150,000 campaign to expand health and sanitation programs in Haiti. He worked in rural areas treating yaws and other common ailments from mobile clinics. The clients were primarily poor farmers with no other means of health care, which made Duvalier very popular and earned him the nickname "Papa Doc."#viraltiktok #edutok #xzyabc #blacktiktok

video_description: FranÃ§ois "Papa Doc" Duvalier was the president of Haiti from 1957 to 1971. His son Jean-Claude "Baby Doc" Duvalier took office in 1971 and a popular uprising ousted him in 1986. The Duvalierist regime lasted longer than any other Haitian government, which continued after Baby Doc fled the country. This period was Duvalierism without Duvalier. General Henri Namphy of the Haitian military was the first of a string of Duvalierist military leaders who led Haiti until the election of Jean-Betrand Aristide in 1990. FRANÃ‡OIS DUVALIER was born on April 14, 1907. His father, Duval Duvalier, was born in Martinique and worked as a schoolteacher in Haiti. Duval Duvalier's occupation placed his family firmly into the new middle class created, partially, by the U.S. military occupation of Haiti (1915-1934). Duvalier studied under prominent Haitian nationalists such as Jean Price-Mars and Dumarsais Estime, who was president of Haiti from 1946-1950. Duvalier joined the Bureau of Ethnology founded by Jacques Romain, while under the directorship of Jean Price-Mars. Through them, he participated in the budding Negritude movement and its local Haitian variant, the Indigenist movement. He received his medical degree in 1934 and studied public health at the University of Michigan in 1943. In 1944, Duvalier became part of the Inter-American Commission's $150,000 campaign to expand health and sanitation programs in Haiti. He worked in rural areas treating yaws and other common ailments from mobile clinics. The clients were primarily poor farmers with no other means of health care, which made Duvalier very popular and earned him the nickname "Papa Doc."#viraltiktok #edutok #xzyabc #blacktiktok

voice_to_text: behind me is the Plaza it might be the most famous hotel in all of New York City it's also the location of a beloved Christmas movie Home Alone 2: lost in New York the plaza was built 1890 an original Plaza Hotel was built in this location it had about 400 rooms and was only about eight floors it always had trouble making a profit you see back in 1890 when they built this plaza this area wasn't as populated but in the 10 years after 1890 this area became more and more affluent because of the park by 1905 they realized this was just out of date even though it was only 15 years old and they went ahead and tore it down they built a new plaza in 1907 and that ended up becoming a rich person's paradise you had an ice skating rink in the basement you had food that was cost as much as $50 to $500 per meal back in 1920 1915 that's an insane amount of money to pay for food so a few different companies have owned this hotel Westin has owned this hotel as has Hilton Donald Trump bought the hotel in 1987 for $400 million and that's what led to his famous cameo and Home Alone 2 you see Chris Columbus the director of Home Alone 2 and the production company reached out to Donald Trump and said hey we need to shoot the interiors for a movie he said that's fine as long as I have a cameo they rolled their eyes they shot the cameo fully intending to cut it after post production was over the scene wasn't as bad as they thought they kept it in previews and did it in front of test audiences test audiences loved the scene so much they kept it in the movie and that's why you see Donald Trump every year on Christmas in Home Alone 2: Lost In New York but you can still come to stay at The Plaza like I said it's one of the most famous hotels in all of the city and it's still in operation.
